@MasterJames: I had a look on BSON, however the problem there is that it is not aware of object types and it tries to serialize everything, without knowing what's important and what's not. For instance, if you try to encode a `THREE.SphereGeometry` you will end-up with dozens of faces/vertices/indices, while you could just encode the constructor parameters (optimising for size). This was the idea behind the compile `profiles`.. keeping only the important properties on each parameter. 

Also, you raised a very valid point! I didn't include date objects in the protocol! I got a bit carried away trying to optimise `TypedArrays`.

> I wondered if the synergistic combo is more efficient or if one supersedes the other or which is better or what?

That might actually be true, as @theo-armour  reported on fast networks. And that's why I also tried to define a format for the raw resources (`.jbbsrc` used in the tests).  However I still think that just casting a binary blob to a `TypedArray` is faster than parsing it's JSON representation, but with the speed Javascript gets optimised I am not sure for the future :laughing: 

@theo-armour: Thanks for your test numbers! I was actually looking to find the weakest points of this format. Can you check in the `Network` tab of the developer's console and see if just the loading of the `.jbb`/`.jbbp` takes longer? At least for the first 3 tests, I am positive that you can get a measurable benefit from TypedArrays. I bet that on fast networks you can load in parallel many more resources, and that's the reason behind these numbers.

Perhaps a good  test is to try and load a bundle of many files rather than just a couple..
